					<description><![CDATA[<p>Funding Supports Expansion Of Wastewater Treatment Technology Crew Carbon has raised $25 million to expand its wastewater treatment technology. The raise combines $19 million in Series A equity and $6</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/crew-carbon-raises-25m/" data-wpel-link="internal">Crew Carbon Raises $25M To Scale Wastewater Decarbonisation Technology</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h2>Funding Supports Expansion Of Wastewater Treatment Technology</h2>
<p>Crew Carbon has raised $25 million to expand its wastewater treatment technology. The raise combines $19 million in Series A equity and $6 million in grants and non-dilutive capital. Burnt Island Ventures led the round with support from AP Ventures, Sony Innovation Fund, Builders Vision and other investors. Existing backers also participated in the oversubscribed raise.</p>
<p>The company plans to use the funding to scale operations. It will invest in technology development and expand deployments across utilities. Crew Carbon positions itself as a process intensification platform for wastewater facilities. It helps operators boost performance while reducing operating costs.</p>
<p>The platform is led by CEO Dr Joachim Katchinoff. The company has already secured several long-term RFPs with major utilities across the United States. These contracts help validate its capacity to deliver measurable operational results. They also support broader adoption of carbon removal solutions within existing infrastructure.</p>
<p>Crew Carbon integrates directly into established wastewater systems. The system helps operators improve pollutant removal and boost settleability. It also reduces chemical dependence in day-to-day operations. These improvements allow utilities to increase plant capacity without major capital upgrades.</p>
<h2>Technology Strengthens Plant Efficiency And Cuts Carbon Emissions</h2>
<p>Crew Carbon uses alkaline minerals to optimise essential environmental conditions. It focuses on stabilising pH and alkalinity within treatment processes. This improves biological nutrient removal and enhances settleability. Operators benefit from higher efficiency without major system changes.</p>
<p>The platform also delivers verified carbon removal. The system locks away carbon dioxide in stable mineral forms. This is achieved through reactions that occur naturally during treatment. The carbon remains permanently stored within the process by-products.</p>
<p>Carbon removal buyers value precise measurement. Crew Carbon provides quantifiable, engineered CO2 removals. This aligns with growing corporate demand for measurable climate action. Long-term offtake agreements reflect confidence in the company’s approach.</p>
<p>The company has delivered removal credits to several major buyers through Frontier. These include global technology companies and industrial partners. Buyers value verified data that demonstrates long-term environmental impact. Crew Carbon has expanded its credit pipeline to more than $33 million.</p>
<p>Utilities also benefit from cost savings. Chemical usage decreases as biological performance improves. Several plants have considered delaying large capital upgrades due to operational gains. One utility has reported that a major infrastructure project may no longer be required.</p>
<h2>Market Need Grows As Utilities Face Stricter Requirements</h2>
<div id="attachment_201272" style="width: 1322px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-201272" class="size-full wp-image-201272" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/crew-2.png" alt="Illustration of wastewater treatment facilities enhanced by AI-driven optimisation systems, showing reduced chemical use, improved efficiency, and real-time environmental monitoring." width="1312" height="736" /><p id="caption-attachment-201272" class="wp-caption-text">Rising regulatory pressure is driving utilities toward advanced wastewater solutions, with AI-enabled systems improving treatment efficiency, reducing chemical dependency, and enabling transparent carbon removal measurement across global facilities. Source: Created by Ventureburn.</p></div>
<p>Wastewater treatment systems face rising regulatory pressure. Many facilities manage higher volumes with ageing infrastructure. Treatment costs have doubled over the past two decades. Utilities need solutions that increase capacity at lower cost. Crew Carbon’s technology supports this shift.</p>
<p>It fits directly into existing processes without major construction. Operators see measurable results within weeks of deployment. The company also provides continuous monitoring and optimisation. The wastewater sector faces challenges related to chemical usage. Many plants rely on costly additives to stabilise biological processes.</p>
<p>These substances increase operational risk and environmental impact. Crew Carbon reduces the need for such chemicals through stable mineral dosing. The company has deployed solutions at nearly ten treatment facilities across the United States and Europe. These include major utilities such as HRSD. The technology improves treatment consistency while supporting carbon removal.</p>
<p>Crew Carbon has also developed measurement, reporting and verification capabilities. These systems ensure high-confidence carbon removal data. The platform provides accurate tracking for both utilities and carbon credit buyers. This supports transparent climate accounting across sectors.</p>
<p>More News: <a href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https://ventureburn.com/synthetic-raises-10m-seed-funding-for-ai-bookkeeping-platform/&amp;sa=D&amp;source=editors&amp;ust=1778843108041842&amp;usg=AOvVaw0g6Oz4Mfoe07lzGW_zVZzL" data-wpel-link="external" rel="external noopener noreferrer">Synthetic Raises $10M Seed Funding For AI Bookkeeping Platform</a></p>
<h2>Company Strengthens Position In Emerging Carbon Removal Market</h2>
<p>Crew Carbon advances within a fast-growing carbon removal landscape. Corporations seek engineered removals to meet net-zero commitments. Buyers prefer solutions with measurable environmental benefits. Crew Carbon’s model aligns with these requirements.</p>
<p>The company leverages existing infrastructure for scalable carbon removal. Wastewater plants represent a global footprint for potential <a href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/it-automation&amp;sa=D&amp;source=editors&amp;ust=1775045537721212&amp;usg=AOvVaw1UvzXiGi0P6rcmGJXIAmJE" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external">decarbonisation</a>. These networks offer opportunities for cost-efficient climate impact. Crew Carbon positions its technology within these systems.</p>
<p>The company recently won a $2.3 million award from the Colorado Energy Office. The award supports further deployment and validation. Additional grants help strengthen the technology’s commercial pathway. These funds complement the Series A capital.</p>
<p>Crew Carbon continues to expand its team to support growth. New roles focus on process technology and system development. The company aims to scale deployments across more utilities. It also plans to expand its analytics platform for operational insights.</p>
<p>The firm remains focused on measurable results for utilities. Its technology has captured more than 2,000 tons of CO2 to date. This has been achieved at rates faster than comparable suppliers. These results strengthen long-term customer confidence.</p>
<p>To stay updated on crypto venture capital funding and market trends, visit our <a href="https://www.google.com/url?q=https://ventureburn.com/category/news/venture-capital/&amp;sa=D&amp;source=editors&amp;ust=1778843108043581&amp;usg=AOvVaw0q0Kt2SPvhLghgMuEUFPqo" data-wpel-link="external" rel="external noopener noreferrer">venture capital news section</a> for more insights.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/crew-carbon-raises-25m/" data-wpel-link="internal">Crew Carbon Raises $25M To Scale Wastewater Decarbonisation Technology</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
